etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in George Wharton (1617–1681), astrologer and royalist. From post-classical Latin superterraneus + -an, probably after subterranean. Compare earlier superterraneous and superterraneal

definitions: That is, lives, or takes place above or on the surface of the earth; of or relating to the region above ground. Chiefly in contrast with subterranean.
A being or creature that dwells above ground or on the surface of the earth.
With the. That which is above ground; the superterranean world or sphere.
